    Demonstration Guide (SOL 700) Explicit Nonlinear Modeling the JWL Explosion using 1-D Spherical Symmetry136 Main Index B. 1-D Spherical Symmetric to 3-D Remap Model Description Blast wave simulations with structures pose a meshing problem when the distance between the structure and the charge is relatively large. As an example, consider a spherical charge of 1kg TNT explosive, with a charge radius of about 50mm, and a structure placed at a distance of 1 meter. It is reasonable to mesh the space between the charge and the structure with 20mm cells, but such meshing is not suitable for representing the explosive charge. (Especially if it is desired to use the JWL burn logic which requires many cells along the charge radius in order to obtain reliable modeling of the detonation). A possible workaround is the use of a biased mesh, starting with small elements near the charge and larger elements near the structure. This can help to a certain degree, but it has the disadvantage of the time step being controlled by the small elements during the entire simulation. SOL 700 has a specific feature to handle such a situation. The simulation is carried out in two stages. First, a spherical (1-D) calculation is carried out with a fine mesh to a desired time that would bring the blast wave in close proximity of the structure. Second, the spherical solution is mapped into the 3-D mesh which includes the structure. The remapping of the fine mesh solution into the 3-D relatively coarse mesh is accomplished with mass, energy and momentum conservation. The model consists of a cube with dimensions of 1m x 1m x 1m, with its origin at [0,0,0] and occupying the positive quadrant ( Figure 3-21). A spherical charge is assumed to be placed with its center coinciding with the origin. Thus only one eighth of the charge will be included in the cube. The cube is meshed with a uniform Cartesian mesh, 80 x 80 x 80. The boundary walls are assumed rigid (by default). Time history of four gauge points will be created: 1.[0.999,0.001,0.001] 2.[0.707,0.001,0.707] 3.[0.577,0.577,0.577] 4.[0.001,0.001,0.001] The first three points are at a range of 1m from the origin. The first point serves to get the reflected pressure from a rigid wall, the second and third are for incident pressure. Figure 3-21 Model for Spherical Symmetry Remap

JWL Material Model vs. The Ideal Gas Approximation In blast wave simulations the choice of the material model of the explosive is quite important. Some explosive material models (EOSJWL,EOSIG) require very fine meshes to give useful results while others (EOSGAM) can give inaccurate results close to the explosive. The following example gives and illustrates a guideline for choosing the optimal material model for the explosive. The material models that can be used for modeling explosives are EOSIG, EOSJWL, and EOSGAM. EOSIG is closest to the physics of detonation and should be used when there is any question whether the explosive will ignite. EOSIG will ignite if the explosive material reaches locally a critical density. For use of EOSIG refer Time = 1.2 ms Time = 1.2 ms Time = 1.2 ms(a) Normal 3-D Run (b) Spher_sym 1-D run (c) 3-D Remap Run Normal 3-D Run 1-D-3-D Remap Run

If ignition is certain, then EOSJWL or EOSGAM can be used. They assume that the explosive will ignite and that the burn front will expand in space. EOSJWL allows to model the propagation of burning zone within the explosive by use of the DETSPH entry. EOSGAM does not model the burning process but assumes that the entire explosive is fully ignited instantaneously and that the explosive products are at rest. EOSGAM then allows modeling the expansion of these explosive products. Of all models, EOSIG will be the most accurate, but often the accuracy of EOSJWL suffices. And even in many instances, the accuracy of EOSGAM is more than sufficient from the engineering point of view. The disadvantage of EOSJWL and of EOSIG over EOSGAM is that EOSJWL and EOSIG require very fine meshes to function properly. This demands much longer computation time. If the distance between target and explosive is sufficiently large, EOSGAM can be a good alternative. T o justify the use of EOSGAM note that in a large space it is not important to resolve the detonation process in great detail, and therefore we may use a so-called “static” detonation model, or the “constant volume” detonation model. This model can be described as detonating an explosive charge within a virtual rigid box and letting the detonation products reach an equilibrium state characterized by a uniform density, a uniform specific internal energy, and zero velocity. Then, the virtual rigid box is removed and the detonation products are allowed to interact with the surrounding medium. This static detonation model gives the ideal gas approximation of blast waves. Therefore a good criterion when the use of EOSGAM is sufficiently accurate can save much CPU time. Close to the explosive EOSJWL will give substantially more accurate results than EOSGAM. As a rule of thumb, the EOSGAM approximation becomes less accurate for scaled ranges R/W1/3 (where R is the range and W is the mass of the high explosive) below about 0.9m/kg1/3. The simulations below will illustrate this rule. This rule is accepted in the field of blast wave simulations and can be used as a guideline to choose between EOSJWL or EOSGAM. By choosing a negative detonation time on the DETSPH, EOSJWL will act as an EOSGAM. Here the ideal gas constant of EOSGAM is given by = 1 + , where  is the last of the JWL parameters. Furthermore, the burn logic is replaced by instantaneously ignition. In this example, EOSGAM is specified as an EOSJWL with negative detonation velocity. As an example we choose a charge of 1 kg Composition C-4, and we compare incident pressure time history and impulse (The integral of over-pressure with time for the positive phase of the wave), at three ranges from the charge center: 1m, 0.5m, 0.25m. In the simulation below spherical symmetry will be used and the meshes will be 1-D. This is to keep run time limited. Repeating the same calculations with 3-D meshes will give the same findings. In principle, these 1-D spherical solutions can be mapped on to a 3-D mesh as illustrated in the topic Modeling the JWL Explosion using 1-D Spherical Symmetry .     Demonstration Guide (SOL 700) Explicit Nonlinear JWL Material Model vs. The Ideal Gas Approximation146 Main Index At the far range of 1.0m, the simplified Static Detonation model agrees very well with the JWL algorithm in terms of both peak pressure (less than 1%) and impulse (~1% up to 1ms, taking into account the time shift). For the intermediate range of 0.5m, the peak pressure agrees within ~7% but the impulse is still within 1%, which is still acceptable as a practical engineering approximation. But for the short range of 0.25m, the peak pressure of the simplified model is under-predicted by as much as 25%, and the impulse is over-predicted by 15%, an unacceptable approximation in most cases. In practice, it can be an option to use for both the explosive products and the air the same  provided they are sufficiently close. This would allow the use of the first and second-order single material solvers. (If there are no other Eulerian materials). The accuracy would decrease a little because of the changed , but would also increase somewhat because only one Eulerian material is modeled. Then the small inaccuracies that come with modeling the multi-material interface between explosive product and air are avoided. The computed results compare well with experimental results predicted by the ConWep experimental data base for the one meter range. For the closer ranges, the differences between the calculated and the ConWep values become more pronounced, as is shown in Table 1. Refining the mesh is expected to improve the agreement. Figure 3-24 Over-pressure Time-history as Function of Mesh Resolution Multiple Charges with Varying Ignition The blast wave created by multiple explosions is an important safety issue for ammunition magazines. In certain cases, it is important to take into account the delay time of the ignition of the various charges present in the magazine. The inclusion of multiple charges with identical ignition times in a SOL 700 input deck is standard. This works with both the JWL algorithm and the simplified model. A more complex situation arises when the charges have different ignition times. According to the JWL algorithm, ignition of the explosive may be triggered by a pressure rise. Therefore the blast wave from one charge (“donor”) may cause the ignition of a neighboring charge (“acceptor”). As a result, if the blast wave from the donor charge arrives at the acceptor charge earlier than the ignition time ( TDET ) set for the acceptor, the acceptor ignites.TIME, msOver-Pressure, MPa 0.4 0.5 0.6 0.7 0.8 0.9 1 1.1 1.2-0.200.20.40.60.811.2Pressure-200 cells/m Pressure-400 cells/m Pressure-800 cells/m 0.9349 MPa, ConWep 1.0078 MPa Kinney 1kg TNT at 1m Range
